          "body": "The chapter's positive section (5:15-20) is not a consolation prize after the negative warnings — it is a full, warm vision of covenant eros that the father commends with the same intensity he used to warn against its counterfeit. The water-imagery is the chapter's most sustained metaphor: cistern, well, fountain, springs, streams (5:15-16). Pure water from a contained source that belongs exclusively to you — the image communicates both refreshment and fidelity, abundance and exclusivity. The springs must not be dispersed in the streets (5:16) because their value depends on belonging to the husband alone (5:17). The covenant wife is to be rejoiced in (5:18), her love is to captivate 'at all times' (5:19), her breasts are to satisfy — language that the Song of Solomon will develop extensively, and that the New Testament will recall when Paul commands husbands to rejoice in their own wives (1 Corinthians 7:2-5; Ephesians 5:25-29). This is not merely permission for marital sexuality; it is a command to active, sustained, exclusive covenant delight."
