        "title": "The cost named — vigor, years, wealth, health, and honor forfeited",
        "range": "5:7-14",
        "excerpt": "Keep your way far from her and do not go near the door of her house, or you will give your vigor to others and your years to the cruel one.",
        "body": "Having shown what the forbidden woman is (5:3-6), the father pivots at verse 7 with the Hebrew attah ('now then') — a discourse marker signaling that the description is complete and the application is beginning. The 'sons' (plural) suggests that the instruction is publicly transmittable, not only to one son but to all who would hear wisdom. The command in verse 8 is notably spatial and prophylactic: not 'be strong when near her' but 'keep your way far' and 'do not go near the door.' Wisdom's strategy is not heroic resistance at the threshold but preventive distance from the address. This anticipates the fuller scenario of chapter 7, where the foolish young man's mistake is precisely that he walks 'near her corner' (7:8).\n\nVerses 9-10 enumerate the losses with a specificity that suggests the father has watched this destruction before. Hod (vigor, 5:9) — the word used of royal splendor, physical vitality, the prime of life — is given away. Years go to the 'cruel one' (akhzari) — a term of moral severity used of those who show no mercy; most likely the wronged husband or the legal apparatus that would pursue the adulterer (Leviticus 20:10; Deuteronomy 22:22). Strangers sava (feast on) the son's koach (strength, wealth) and his hard labor enriches an alien house. The financial ruin depicted here is not merely metaphorical: in the ancient Near East, adultery could result in legal enslavement, forced labor, and forfeiture of property.\n\nVerses 11-14 are the chapter's most psychologically penetrating section. The son is made to overhear his own future lament in the first person. The groaning arrives at the acharit — the final end — when flesh (basar) and body (sheer) are consumed (kalah). The ancient commentators, including the Talmud and the church fathers, consistently read this as venereal disease; the physical wasting is the body's testimony against the choices made. The lament in verses 12-13 names the root failure: not just the act of adultery but the prior refusal of musar (discipline) and tokhechah (reproof). The sin of the bedroom traces back to the unteachable ear of the classroom. And verse 14 adds the social dimension: near-total ruin 'in the midst of the assembly' (qahal). Public shame before the covenant community is the final earthly consequence.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Hod* (vigor, 5:9) — typically used of the splendor of kings and warriors (Psalm 21:5; Numbers 27:20); its loss to a stranger is a royal-dignity image. *Musar* (discipline, 5:12, 23) — the same word the book introduced in 1:2-3 as the purpose of Proverbs itself. The man who rejects Proverbs dies for lack of the very thing Proverbs offers. *Qahal* (assembly, 5:14) — the covenantal gathering of Israel; public shame before qahal is shame before the people of God, not merely social embarrassment."
